<h1>Hike Laguna Chicabal Quetzaltenango</h1><p>&nbsp;Hiking Laguna de Chicabal offers a unique opportunity to explore one of the most sacred and beautiful sites in Quetzaltenango. Located in San Martín Sacatepéquez at an altitude of 2,900 meters (8,898 feet), this lagoon lies within the crater of Volcano Chicabal and serves as a ceremonial center for the Mam (Maya) population in the region. The lagoon is encircled by lush cloud forests, creating a magical and serene environment. From the western side of the volcano, hikers can enjoy views of Volcán Santa María and Santiaguito.</p><iframe width="100%" height="550" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/EZGVb-NR3ug" title="YouTube video player" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share" referrerpolicy="strict-origin-when-cross-origin" allowfullscreen></iframe>
<p>&nbsp;The hike requires a minimum of two participants, with a cost of Q275.00 or US$40 per person. The price includes private transportation from Casa Xelajú to the park and the admission fee. Cancellations are accepted up to 24 hours before the hike. Participants are advised to bring sturdy hiking shoes, ample water, snacks, a raincoat, and a jacket to ensure comfort and safety during the trek.</p>
<p>&nbsp;In the morning, the journey begins from Quetzaltenango to San Martín Sacatepéquez, also known as San Martín Chile Verde. The bus drops hikers two kilometers south of the village, where the walking portion of the hike begins. From this point, hikers proceed to the main entrance of Laguna de Chicabal Park, ascend to the summit, and then descend approximately 780 steps into the crater to reach the lagoon. The uphill hike typically takes about two hours, with the return journey taking approximately one hour. The hike is moderately difficult and is not recommended for individuals with knee problems.</p><a href="https://www.casaxelaju.com/hiking-laguna-de-chicabal/"><b><span style="font-size: x-large;">Hike Laguna Chicabal Quetzaltenango</span></b></a><br />
<p>&nbsp;As Laguna de Chicabal is a Mam ceremonial center, visitors are asked to respect ongoing ceremonies along the lake’s shores. Swimming is strictly prohibited, as the local community regards the lagoon as a sacred site. Recognized by experts as a “natural jewel in Guatemala,” this hike provides both a cultural and scenic experience that is truly unforgettable.</p>
